<section xml:id="section-surface-integrals">
  <title>Surface Integrals</title>
  <p>
    Recall the definition of the line integral.
    <me>
      \int_{\gamma} F \cdot T ds = \int_a^b F(\gamma(t)) \cdot
      \gamma^\prime(t) dt
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    On the left, we started with intrinsic information, using the
    arclength parametrization and infinitesimal <m>ds</m> to build a
    definition which didn't depends on parametrization. Then we
    showed, using <m>ds = |\gamma^\prime(t)| dt</m> how to calculate
    the line integral for an arbitrary the description of length in
    terms of the parametrization. We have something similar for
    surfaces. Instead of length, we have an infinitesimal area
    <m>dA</m> which is independent of the parametrization. If
    <m>\sigma(u,v)</m> is a function of the parameters <m>u</m> and
    <m>v</m> on a simply connected domain <m>D</m>, through a change
    of variables, we can express the intrinsic <m>dA</m> in terms of
    the specific parameters <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>. For curves, the
    mediating factor was the length of the tangent; for surfaces, it
    is the length of the normal.
    <me>
      dA = |\sigma_u \times \sigma_v| du dv
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    This gives us a local area differential for integration.
  </p>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\sigma(u,v)</m> be a parametric surface defined on a
        simply connected open set <m>D</m>. Let <m>f</m> be a scalar
        field defined in a neighbourhood of the surface <m>\sigma</m>.
        The integral of <m>f</m> over <m>\sigma</m> is defined as
        follows.
        <me>
          \int_\sigma f dA = \int_D f(\sigma(u,v)) |\sigma_u \times
          \sigma_v | du dv
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    This definition lets us calculate surface area of parametric
    surfaces. To find area, we just integrate the constant scalar
    field <m>f = 1</m>.
    <me>
      A = \int_\sigma 1 dA = \int_D |\sigma_u \times \sigma_v| du dv
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    If we expand this out, we can get the full expression in all its
    complexity.
    <me>
      A = \int_D \sqrt{ \left( \frac{\del \sigma_2}{\del u} \frac{\del
      \sigma_3}{\del v} - \frac{\del \sigma_2}{\del v} \frac{\del
      \sigma_3}{\del u} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\del \sigma_3}{\del
      u} \frac{\del \sigma_1}{\del v} - \frac{\del \sigma_3}{\del v}
      \frac{\del \sigma_1}{\del u} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\del
      \sigma_1}{\del u} \frac{\del \sigma_2}{\del v} - \frac{\del
      \sigma_1}{\del v} \frac{\del \sigma_2}{\del u} \right)^2 } du
      dv
    </me>
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\sigma</m> be the graph of a function <m>f: \RR^2
        \rightarrow \RR</m> as defined in <xref
        ref="example-surface-graph" />. Then we can use the area
        formula to write the general equation of the surface area of
        the graph of <m>f</m> over a simply-connected region <m>D</m>
        in its domain.
        <me>
          A = \int_D \sqrt{ \left( \frac{\del f}{\del x} \right)^2 +
          \left( \frac{\del f}{\del y} \right)^2 + 1} dx dy
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f: [a,b] \rightarrow \RR</m> be a differentiable
        function and let <m>\sigma</m> is a surface of revolution as
        defined in <xref ref="example-surface-revolution" />. Let <m>D
        = [a,b] \times [0,2\pi]</m>. Then we can define the surface of
        such a general surface of revolution.
        <me>
          A = \int_D \sqrt{ 1 - \left( \frac{\del f}{\del x}
          \right)^2} f(x) dx
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The parabaloid <m>z = k(x^2 +y^2)</m> can be described by
        <m>\sigma(u,v) = (u,v,k(u^2+v^2))</m> over <m>D</m> a circle
        of radius <m>r</m>. We can calculate its surface area.
        <md>
          <mrow>
            A \amp = \int_D \sqrt{4k^2 u^2 + 4k^2 v^w + 1} du dv
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^r \sqrt{4k^2 r^2 + 1} r dr d
            \theta
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            u \amp = 4k^2 r^1 + 1 \implies du = 8k^2 r dr
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = 2\pi \int_1^{4hk} \sqrt{u} \frac{1}{8k^2} du
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = \left. \frac{\pi}{4k^2} \frac{2u^{\frac{3}{2}}}{3}
            \right|_1^{4kh}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = \frac{\pi}{6k^2} \left( (4kh)^{\frac{3}{2}} -1
            \right) = \frac{2\sqrt{h^3k^3} - 1}{6k^2}
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The surface of revolution under <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{x}</m> for
        <m>x \in [1,\infty)</m> is called the Horn of Gabriel. It can
        be described parametrically for <m>(x,\theta) \in [1, \infty)
        \times [0, 2\pi]</m> as the following surface.
        <me>
          \sigma(x,\theta) = \left( x, \frac{\cos \theta}{x},
          \frac{\sin \theta}{x} \right)
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        The surface area of the Horn of Gabriel is quite interesting.
        (The comparison results for single-variable integrals are
        useful in this calculation.)
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \sigma_x \amp = \left( 1, \frac{-\cos \theta}{x^2},
            \frac{-\sin \theta}{x^2} \right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \sigma_{\theta} \amp = \left( 0, \frac{-\sin \theta}{x},
            \frac{\cos \theta}{x} \right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \sigma_x \times \sigma_{\theta} \amp = \left(
            \frac{-1}{x^3}, \frac{\cos \theta}{x}, \frac{-\sin
            \theta}{x} \right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            |\sigma_x \times \sigma_\theta| \amp = \sqrt{
            \frac{1}{x^6} + \frac{1}{x^2}} = \frac{1}{x} \sqrt{
            \frac{1}{x^4} + 1}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            A \amp = \int_\sigma 1 = \int_1^{\infty} \int_0^{2\pi}
            \frac{1}{x} \sqrt{ \frac{1}{x^4} + 1} d\theta dx
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = 2\pi \int_1^{\infty} \frac{1}{x} \sqrt{
            \frac{1}{x^4} + 1} dx \geq 2\pi \int_1^\infty \frac{1}{x}
            = \infty
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Compare this surface are with the volume of the Horn of
        Gabriel.
        <md>
          <mrow>
            V \amp = \int_1^{\infty} \int_0^{\frac{1}{x}}
            \int_0^{2\pi} r d \theta dr dx
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = 2\pi \int_1^\infty \left. \frac{r^2}{2}
            \right|_0^{\frac{1}{x}} = 2\pi \int_1^\infty
            \frac{1}{2x^2} dx
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = \left. \frac{2\pi}{2} \frac{-1}{x} \right|_1^\infty
            = \pi
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a very strange situation: an object with finite volume
        and infinite surface area.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>
